         <abstract>
            <p>The most widely employed method for a numerical solution of a symmetric integral equation with kernel $K(x, t)$ in interval $I \equiv \lbrack a, b \rbrack$ is the replacement of the original problem by the sequence of eigenproblems $$K^{(n)}y^{(n)}_i = \mu_{in} y^{(n)}_i, \quad K^{(n)} \equiv \{w_{jn}K(x_{in}, x_{jn})\},\quad i = 1,\ldots, n$$, with $w_{jn} &gt; 0$ and $x_{jn} \in I, j = 1,\ldots, n$. The eigenvectors $y^{(n)}_i$ are further used to obtain an approximation, with improved error estimates, of the numerical eigensolution for some $N &gt; n$, with no necessity of computing $\mu_{iN}$ and $y^{(N)}_i, i = 1,\ldots, N$, and of constructing another matrix.</p>
          </abstract>
